    return return_code;
}

List additional symbols that are required to analyze the target function to determine if the target function code violates the following MISRA C rule:
A project shall not contain dead code. Any operation that is executed but whose removal would not affect program behaviour constitutes dead code. Notes:
1. The behaviour of an embedded sytem is often determined not just by the nature of its actions, but also by the time at which they occur.
2. unreachable code is not dead code, as it cannot be executed.
3.Initialization is not the same as an assignment operation and is therfore not a candidate for dead code.

Explain why each symbol is required in the analysis of the target function for the MISRA C rule.
explanation:
To decide whether OS_SelectMultiple is dead code you must know (a) whether it is ever called from the rest of the program and (b) whether the work it does has externally observable effects. The following symbols are required for that analysis:

- OS_SelectMultiple_Impl
  - Direct callee from OS_SelectMultiple. Its implementation determines whether removing OS_SelectMultiple would remove observable behaviour (side effects, global state changes, I/O, timing). Without this, you cannot tell if the wrapper is the only caller site or if its removal changes behaviour.

- OS_FdSet_ConvertIn_Impl
  - One of the functions called by OS_SelectMultiple_Impl (per the call graph). It may perform conversions with side effects (e.g. touching global state, validating/normalizing fd sets) that affect program behaviour or timing.

- OS_DoSelect
  - The core select operation called by the Impl. This is the most likely place of externally observable effects (blocking/timing, interaction with OS/hardware). Its presence or absence determines whether the path is doing meaningful work or could be removed.

- OS_FdSet_ConvertOut_Impl
  - The post-select conversion back into user-visible FD sets. It may modify caller-visible data structures; thus needed to judge whether removing OS_SelectMultiple would change observable behaviour.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler
- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr
  - These unit-test / stub framework symbols appear in the static call graph associated with OS_SelectMultiple. They can indicate that calls in the function are replaced or wrapped by test stubs, conditional macros, or instrumentation. You must inspect these to determine whether the calls in OS_SelectMultiple are compile-time/test-only artifacts (which could make the function dead in production) or actual runtime behaviour.

- OS_SymbolLookup
- OS_ModuleSymbolLookup
  - Functions that provide dynamic symbol/module lookup. If OS_SelectMultiple can be referenced indirectly through dynamic lookup (module symbol tables, plugins, shell/console commands), removal may affect behaviour even if there are no static callers. These symbols are necessary to decide if the function is reachable/used indirectly.

- OS_API_Init
  - Initialization code frequently registers APIs, tables or command handlers. If OS_SelectMultiple is registered/unregistered during initialization, it may be used indirectly by other code (CLI, RPC, or API dispatch). Inspecting OS_API_Init helps determine whether the function is exposed and therefore not dead.

Together these symbols let an analyst determine: whether OS_SelectMultiple is actually invoked (statically or dynamically), whether it (or its callees) perform externally observable actions (I/O, timing, global state), and whether unit-test instrumentation masks or replaces behaviour. Without these, one cannot reliably decide if removing OS_SelectMultiple would be behaviour-preserving (dead) or not.
